# The Ledger — Core Rules (read before EVERY response)

**These rules bind EVERY agent equally — Claude Code AND every Cursor agent (Auto, cloud
agents, background agents). No agent is exempt.** This is the one file all of them reload every
turn (`alwaysApply: true`). The owner approved these standards once; they are concrete and
persist until the owner explicitly changes them. If you are about to ask the owner something,
or deviate from a format — STOP and check this file and the file it points to first. The
detailed specs already exist; use them. Re-requesting approved information — by any agent — is
the specific failure this file was created to stop.

---

## 1. How to operate (the anti-ignore rules — these are why this file exists)

- **The spec already exists — read it, never re-ask.** Before asking the owner ANY question
  about a standard, format, count, or past decision, read the file that owns the answer
  (table in §2). Only ask if the answer is genuinely not in any file — and then say
  "this isn't recorded in <file>" so the gap is known. Re-requesting approved information is
  the #1 failure this file prevents.
- **A spec violation is never a question.** If data or UI breaks a written rule, fix it
  against the rule decisively. Do not ship it, do not ask if it's acceptable.
- **Be decisive.** On routine/verified calls (merge a green PR, reconcile a stale checkpoint,
  commit verified work, apply a written standard) — act and report. Do not lay out options and
  ask which to pick. Escalate ONLY genuine scope changes, credibility tradeoffs between
  conflicting sources, or irreversible/destructive actions.
- **Verify, never trust "done."** Independently check every completion claim (especially
  Cursor's) against the actual repo/data/build before accepting it. "It builds" ≠ "it's correct."
- **The demo profiles are the locked spec.** Sanders `S000033` + the 3 other featured profiles
  are concrete. Phase 17b feeds the other 536 members through the SAME components and SAME
  checklist — it never redesigns them. Fix the script/extractor that produced bad data; never
  hand-clean one member and call it done.

